            <h2 class="text-left section-header mb-4 text-center"">The System</h2>
                <p class="paragraph--dark text-left font-size-1">I look at the fundamentals of a company and the price action from 
                charts.
                 The fundamentals ensure the intitutional interest 
                in a companies equity is for real, and the technicals give you the supply/demand picture of the shares.    </p>

                <p class="paragraph--dark text-left font-size-1">Here are the basics.
                </p>

           <ol class="terms-list">
         
            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Overview - Read Bill O'Niel's book "How to Make Money In Stocks".   
             <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Fundamentals - I am looking for earnings growth. 
             I compare the previous year's quarterly earnings for the 
            past one,two, three or four quarters, and look for an acceleration in growth rate.  Earnings can break out becasue of a new product, new catalyst, or
             new management.  I generally don't care if the stock has a high P/E, but a low P/E stock with a good chart means a potential for earnings expansion.  <span></li>

             <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Charts - I buy when a stock breaks out of a trading range.  I look for 
            low volume on distribution, and higher volume during accumulation.  The stock must have good volume when it exits a trading range. Read books on the subject 
            to get the idea.  See the chart below for Qualcom, a very strong performing stock during the 1999 dot com bubble. <span></li>
 <%= image_tag "stock-qcom.png", alt: "QCOM breakout", class: 'picture-1' %>
            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> Insider buying - Execs buying large blocks of shares is always good.  If execs own very little ,and collect 
            fat paychecks, they are probably pieces of shit just like their companies.  Also look for high instituional sponsorship.  If these guys are buying, so will I.    <span></li>

           

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> Indicators - I use price, volume and volatility. 
             When looking at markets, I will look at breath including the McClellan Oscillator, or check Call Put Ratios ($CPCE) to determine sentiment.  <span></li>

           
            <span></li>

         
        
            
            </ol>
